{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515249"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:30:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:30:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12425"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12425"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.68,0.27,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4933"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109885"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4933"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"348"},{"type":"tags","id":"1409"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"6563"},{"type":"tags","id":"6620"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38488"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39997"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41232"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109885"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-minute episode of sudden vision loss in his right eye and left-sided arm weakness that resolved spontaneously. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. He is a current smoker with a 20 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with pulse rate 78/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Neurological examination is normal. A right carotid bruit is audible on auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most crucial next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fundoscopy","Carotid duplex ultrasound","Non-contrast CT head","Transthoracic echocardiogram","Electrocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a transient ischaemic attack (TIA) with ipsilateral transient monocular vision loss (amaurosis fugax) and contralateral arm weakness. While the carotid bruit and vascular risk factors suggest carotid atherosclerotic disease, the initial investigation must exclude intracranial pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-contrast CT head\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it rapidly excludes intracranial haemorrhage, which is important before starting antiplatelet therapy. It can also identify stroke mimics such as subdural haematoma, space-occupying lesions, or established infarction that may not be clinically apparent. Current guidelines recommend urgent brain imaging for all patients with suspected TIA. While MRI is more sensitive and specific than non-contrast CT for diagnosing stroke and TIA when diagnostic confirmation is required, CT remains the commonly used modality in the emergency setting due to its widespread availability, speed, and ability to exclude haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid duplex ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is a crucial investigation for assessing carotid stenosis, particularly in cases with a carotid bruit. However, it should be performed after brain imaging has excluded intracranial pathology and antiplatelet therapy has been initiated. Symptomatic stenosis \u0026gt;70% would require urgent vascular surgical review.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFundoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E could identify retinal pathology such as central retinal vein occlusion (CRVO), which can cause monocular vision loss. However, CRVO typically presents with gradual, painless vision loss over hours to days, often accompanied by persistent visual deficits and characteristic retinal haemorrhages on examination. The brief two-minute duration of symptoms and complete resolution, combined with concurrent contralateral motor symptoms, make a vascular TIA far more likely than CRVO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful to investigate cardioembolic sources of TIA, such as atrial thrombus or valvular vegetations. However, brain imaging takes priority to exclude haemorrhage and guide immediate management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed to detect atrial fibrillation or other arrhythmias that could cause cardioembolism. While important in the TIA workup, it does not take precedence over brain imaging in the acute setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing CT head, this patient would require urgent antiplatelet therapy (if no contraindications), carotid imaging, and expedited vascular review. The presence of a carotid bruit suggests a carotid stenosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urgent neuroimaging is important in patients with suspected TIA to exclude haemorrhage and stroke mimics before initiating antiplatelet therapy.","Non-contrast CT head remains the commonly used modality in the emergency setting due to its widespread availability, speed, and ability to exclude haemorrhage."],"references":["Leung ES, Hamilton-Bruce MA, Koblar SA. Transient ischaemic attacks - assessment and management. Aust Fam Physician. 2010 Nov;39(11):820-4. PMID: 21301653. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2010/november/transient-ischaemic-attacks","Queensland Health, Royal Flying Doctor Service (Queensland Section) and Apunipima Cape York Health Council (2024) Chronic Conditions Manual: Prevention and Management of Chronic Conditions in Rural and Remote Australia 3rd edition 2024, Office of Rural and Remote Health, Clinical Excellence Queensland, Queensland Health.","Stroke Foundation. Australian and New Zealand Living Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management. Available at https://informme.org.au/en/Guidelines/Clinical-Guidelines-for-Stroke-Management. Accessed [02 July 2025]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12425"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T13:21:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T13:23:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4933"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109885"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null